06647nam a22008415i 9780857450777DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574507777 a10.1515/97808574507772doi  a(DE-B1597)636932  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHT1521b.R4185 7aSOC0700002bisacsh00aRacism in the Modern World :bHistorical Perspectives on Cultural Transfer and Adaptation /ced. by Simon Wendt, Manfred Berg. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Racism in the Modern World: Historical Perspectives on Cultural Transfer and Adaptation -- t1. The Racialization of the Globe: Historical Perspectives -- t2. How Racism Arose in Europe and Why It Did Not in the Near East -- t3. Culture’s Shadow: “Race” and Postnational Belonging in the Twentieth Century -- t4. Racism and Genocide -- t5. Slavery and Racism in Nineteenth-Century Cuba -- t6. Toward a Transnational History of Racism: Wilhelm Marr and the Interrelationships between Colonial Racism and German Anti-Semitism -- t7. Transatlantic Anthropological Dialogue and “the Other”: Felix von Luschan’s Research in America, 1914–1915 -- t8. Transits of Race: Empire and Difference in Philippine-American Colonial History -- t9. Interrogating Caste and Race in South Asia -- t10. The Making of a “Ruling Race”: Defining and Defending Whiteness in Colonial India -- t11. Glocalizing “Race” in China: Concepts and Contingencies at the Turn of the Twentieth Century -- t12. Race without Supremacy: On Racism in the Political Discourse of Late Meiji Japan, 1890–1912 -- t13. Hendrik Verwoerd’s Long March to Apartheid: Nationalism and Racism in South Africa -- t14. The “Right Kind of White People”: Reproducing Whiteness in the United States and Australia, 1780s–1930s -- t15. Race and Indigeneity in Contemporary Australia -- tNotes on Contributors -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEmphasizing the global nature of racism, this volume brings together historians from various regional specializations to explore this phenomenon from comparative and transnational perspectives. The essays shed light on how racial ideologies and practices developed, changed, and spread in Europe, Asia, the Near East, Australia, and Africa, focusing on processes of transfer, exchange, appropriation, and adaptation. To what extent, for example, were racial beliefs of Western origin? Did similar belief systems emerge in non-Western societies independently of Western influence? And how did these societies adopt and adapt Western racial beliefs once they were exposed to them? Up to this point, the few monographs or edited collections that exist only provide students of the history of racism with tentative answers to these questions. More importantly, the authors of these studies tend to ignore transnational processes of exchange and transfer. Yet, as this volume shows, these are crucial to an understanding of the diffusion of racial belief systems around the globe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Race & Ethnic Relations.2bisacsh1 aBarth, Boris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerg, Manfred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerg, Manfred, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBraude, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruns, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDharampal-Frick, Gita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela